1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,879
Lesson 1: A Different Way of Thinking.

2
00:00:03,879 --> 00:00:08,388
In this course, we'll explore systems
thinking, a discipline that helps us see

3
00:00:08,388 --> 00:00:11,960
complexity more clearly and make better
decisions as a result.

4
00:00:12,960 --> 00:00:17,354
In this first lesson, we'll explain what
systems thinking is and contrast it with

5
00:00:17,354 --> 00:00:19,276
linear, cause-and-effect reasoning.

6
00:00:20,276 --> 00:00:22,180
Let's begin with an example.

7
00:00:23,180 --> 00:00:25,177
A customer service team is under
pressure.

8
00:00:25,177 --> 00:00:28,196
Complaints are piling up and response
times are slipping.

9
00:00:28,196 --> 00:00:33,302
The obvious solution seems clear: hire
more staff. For a few weeks, things

10
00:00:33,302 --> 00:00:33,862
improve.

11
00:00:33,862 --> 00:00:38,317
Six months later however, the complaint
backlog is back, and this time it's

12
00:00:38,317 --> 00:00:38,738
larger.

13
00:00:38,738 --> 00:00:40,503
So, what went wrong?

14
00:00:41,503 --> 00:00:47,049
The problem is linear thinking. Linear
thinking follows a simple chain: problem

15
00:00:47,049 --> 00:00:49,537
leads to cause, cause leads to fix.

16
00:00:49,537 --> 00:00:53,868
It works well for problems that are
genuinely simple and isolated, like a

17
00:00:53,868 --> 00:00:57,478
broken piece of equipment, or a single
missing piece of data.

18
00:00:57,478 --> 00:01:02,036
However, most professional problems
aren't like this. They involve multiple

19
00:01:02,036 --> 00:01:06,162
actors, competing pressures, and outcomes
that take time to surface.

20
00:01:06,162 --> 00:01:10,717
When we apply linear thinking to those
kinds of problems, we often get answers

21
00:01:10,717 --> 00:01:15,035
that are partially right in the short
term but wrong over time, in ways we

22
00:01:15,035 --> 00:01:16,100
didn't anticipate.

23
00:01:16,100 --> 00:01:20,698
In our customer service example, adding
staff reduced visible pressure, and that

24
00:01:20,698 --> 00:01:25,063
reduced pressure changed how leadership
prioritised the underlying problems.

25
00:01:25,063 --> 00:01:30,471
With urgency removed, the root causes of
complaints, that is: unclear processes

26
00:01:30,471 --> 00:01:34,769
and poor handoffs between teams, were
never properly addressed.

27
00:01:34,769 --> 00:01:38,624
The system adapted around the fix, and
the problem returned.

28
00:01:40,624 --> 00:01:44,061
So, how do we know when a problem is
systemic rather than isolated?

29
00:01:44,061 --> 00:01:46,383
There are a few reliable signals.

30
00:01:47,383 --> 00:01:51,852
The first is that the same problem keeps
returning, even after it appears to have

31
00:01:51,852 --> 00:01:56,154
been fixed. If a solution that worked
last year isn't working now, the problem

32
00:01:56,154 --> 00:01:58,947
likely has structural roots that weren't
addressed.

33
00:01:59,947 --> 00:02:04,063
The second signal is that different parts
of the organisation experience the

34
00:02:04,063 --> 00:02:06,588
problem differently, and each blames the
other.

35
00:02:06,588 --> 00:02:11,127
When every team has a reasonable account
of what's going wrong and each account is

36
00:02:11,127 --> 00:02:15,218
at odds with the others, the issue is
almost certainly in the interactions

37
00:02:15,218 --> 00:02:18,244
between those teams, not within any
single one of them.

38
00:02:19,244 --> 00:02:23,006
The third is that well-intentioned
interventions make things worse.

39
00:02:23,006 --> 00:02:27,269
If every fix creates a new problem, the
system is pushing back against the

40
00:02:27,269 --> 00:02:31,940
intervention. That's a strong signal that
the fix isn't addressing the right part

41
00:02:31,940 --> 00:02:32,758
of the system.

42
00:02:33,758 --> 00:02:38,263
Systemic problems are structural, and
can't be resolved with simple fixes.

43
00:02:40,263 --> 00:02:44,303
To tackle systemic problems, we'll use
'systems thinking'.

44
00:02:44,303 --> 00:02:49,306
Systems thinking is a discipline that
focuses on structures, relationships, and

45
00:02:49,306 --> 00:02:54,117
patterns of behaviour over time, rather
than on individual events and single

46
00:02:54,117 --> 00:02:54,566
causes.

47
00:02:55,566 --> 00:02:59,281
'Systems thinking' is an extension of
'analytical thinking'.

48
00:02:59,281 --> 00:03:04,063
Where analytical thinking asks "what
happened?", systems thinking asks "what

49
00:03:04,063 --> 00:03:08,910
keeps producing this?" Where analytical
thinking isolates a variable, systems

50
00:03:08,910 --> 00:03:12,098
thinking looks at the web of connections
around it.

51
00:03:12,098 --> 00:03:16,461
It's worth being clear about what systems
thinking is not. It isn't a method for

52
00:03:16,461 --> 00:03:20,658
analysing every possible variable in a
situation. And it isn't about building

53
00:03:20,658 --> 00:03:23,198
elaborate diagrams before we're allowed
to act.

54
00:03:23,198 --> 00:03:27,641
It's a practical discipline, and the
vocabulary it uses is accessible to any

55
00:03:27,641 --> 00:03:30,721
professional willing to look at problems
differently.

56
00:03:32,721 --> 00:03:37,364
In this course, we'll define what a
system is and examine its structural

57
00:03:37,364 --> 00:03:40,569
building blocks: stocks, flows and
feedback loops.

58
00:03:41,569 --> 00:03:46,462
We'll then explore the characteristic
behaviours that complex systems produce

59
00:03:46,462 --> 00:03:50,068
including delays, emergence, and
unintended consequences.

60
00:03:51,068 --> 00:03:55,310
Finally, we'll discuss how to apply a
systems lens to real decisions at work

61
00:03:55,310 --> 00:03:58,591
through mental models, leverage points
and informed action.

62
00:03:59,591 --> 00:04:04,203
By the end, we'll be able to identify
systemic patterns, avoid common

63
00:04:04,203 --> 00:04:09,223
decision-making traps, and frame problems
in ways that lead to more durable

64
00:04:09,223 --> 00:04:09,901
solutions.

65
00:04:11,901 --> 00:04:14,037
Let's stop the lesson here.

66
00:04:14,037 --> 00:04:18,443
In this lesson, we first examined why
linear, cause-and-effect reasoning

67
00:04:18,443 --> 00:04:21,049
struggles when applied to complex
problems.

68
00:04:21,049 --> 00:04:25,030
We then looked at the signals that tell
us a problem is systemic rather than

69
00:04:25,030 --> 00:04:25,879
straightforward.

70
00:04:25,879 --> 00:04:29,316
Finally, we clarified what systems
thinking is and what it isn't.

